Based on the log you shared, the failure is **not occurring during SSL/TLS connection** (your certificate import looks successful), and it's also **not a Gradle version issue**.

The key error is:

```text
Could not find spring-security-web-6.3.10.jar
(org.springframework.security:spring-security-web:6.3.10).

Searched in:
https://artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443/artifactory/itepaypg-sbiepay2-gradle-virtual/org/springframework/security/spring-security-web/6.3.10/spring-security-web-6.3.10.jar
```

You mentioned that the JAR is available at:

```text
itepaypg-sbiepay2-gradle-virtual/
└── org/springframework/security/spring-security-web/6.3.10/
    └── spring-security-web-6.3.10.jar
```

If that's true, then there are a few likely causes.

---

## 1. Check whether the POM exists

Gradle does **not** usually resolve Maven dependencies using only the JAR.

For Maven repositories, Gradle first looks for:

```text
spring-security-web-6.3.10.pom
```

and then downloads the JAR.

Verify that both files exist:

```text
spring-security-web-6.3.10.pom
spring-security-web-6.3.10.jar
```

under:

```text
org/springframework/security/spring-security-web/6.3.10/
```

If only the JAR exists, Gradle can report:

```text
Could not find spring-security-web-6.3.10.jar
```

even though the JAR is visible in Artifactory.

---

## 2. Verify the artifact is actually downloadable

From the runner host or inside the build container:

```bash
curl -u "$JF_USER:$JF_TOKEN" -I \
"https://artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443/artifactory/itepaypg-sbiepay2-gradle-virtual/org/springframework/security/spring-security-web/6.3.10/spring-security-web-6.3.10.jar"
```

Expected:

```text
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
```

If you get:

```text
401 Unauthorized
403 Forbidden
404 Not Found
```

then Artifactory permissions or repository configuration are the issue.

---

## 3. Check the virtual repository includes the remote/local repo containing Spring artifacts

Even though the artifact appears in the UI, the virtual repository used by CI is:

```yaml
JFROG_GRADLE_REPO:
https://artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443/artifactory/itepaypg-sbiepay2-gradle-virtual/
```

Verify that:

```text
itepaypg-sbiepay2-gradle-virtual
```

includes the repository where Spring Security artifacts reside.

Common issue:

```text
Maven Central Remote
```

was removed from the virtual repository or excluded by a repository pattern.

---

## 4. Check repository permissions for the CI service account

The build authenticates with:

```groovy
credentials {
    username = System.getenv("JF_USER")
    password = System.getenv("JF_TOKEN")
}
```

The UI may show the artifact because your personal account has access, but the GitLab service account may not.

Test using the exact CI credentials:

```bash
curl -u "$JF_USER:$JF_TOKEN" \
"https://artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443/artifactory/itepaypg-sbiepay2-gradle-virtual/org/springframework/security/spring-security-web/6.3.10/spring-security-web-6.3.10.pom"
```

---

## 5. Verify Gradle is actually using the repository from the init script

Your init script configures repositories via:

```groovy
settings.dependencyResolutionManagement {
    repositoriesMode.set(RepositoriesMode.FAIL_ON_PROJECT_REPOS)
    repositories {
        maven {
            url System.getenv("JFROG_GRADLE_REPO")
        }
    }
}
```

This only works if the project uses dependency resolution management correctly.

Run:

```bash
gradle dependencies --info
```

or

```bash
gradle build --info
```

and check whether Gradle logs:

```text
Using Maven repository 'maven'
https://artifactory.jfrog.sbi:443/artifactory/itepaypg-sbiepay2-gradle-virtual/
```

for dependency resolution.

---

## 6. Spring Security 6.3.10 may not actually exist in the repository metadata

I've seen cases where:

```text
spring-security-web-6.3.10.jar
```

was manually uploaded or cached,

but:

```text
maven-metadata.xml
spring-security-web-6.3.10.pom
```

were missing.

Open these URLs directly:

```text
.../spring-security-web/6.3.10/spring-security-web-6.3.10.pom
.../spring-security-web/maven-metadata.xml
```

and verify they return successfully.

---

## 7. Enable dependency resolution debug

Modify the pipeline temporarily:

```yaml
gradle build -x test \
  -Pversion="${VERSION}" \
  --refresh-dependencies \
  --info \
  --stacktrace
```

This will show:

* exact repository queried
* HTTP status returned by Artifactory
* whether Gradle found the POM
* authentication failures

---

## Most likely root cause

Because the error is:

```text
Could not find spring-security-web-6.3.10.jar
```

while the artifact is visible in Artifactory, the most common causes are:

1. **POM file missing** alongside the JAR.
2. **CI service account lacks read permission**.
3. **Artifact visible in UI but not exposed through the virtual repository used by Gradle**.
4. **Gradle is querying a different repository than expected.**

